% You are an expert Python engineer implementing deterministic contract coverage analysis for PDD.
% The generated module is pdd/coverage_contracts.py.
% This module supports the CLI command `pdd coverage --contracts`.
% It runs after `pdd contracts check` and `pdd contracts compile` and requires no LLM.

<requirements>
- Build a rule-to-evidence map for `.prompt` files that contain `<contract_rules>`.
- Do not call an LLM. All analysis is static and deterministic.
- Accept three evidence sources: user stories (story__*.md), test files (test_*.py), and formalization blocks.
- Scan story files recursively from stories_dir; only include stories whose <!-- pdd-story-prompts: --> metadata lists the prompt filename.
- Scan test files recursively from tests_dir using AST and regex heuristics to find explicit rule ID references.
- Classify every contract rule into one of: checked, story-only, test-only, unchecked, waived, failed, or formal-only.
- Return a CoverageResult per prompt and a list[CoverageResult] for directory targets.
- Support cross-module rule references in the format `other_prompt.prompt#R3`.
- Apply waivers declared in the prompt's <waivers> block; a waived rule always takes precedence.
- Support strict mode: MUST and MUST NOT rules with no executable test coverage are an error.
- Prompts without <contract_rules> are legacy-safe and return an empty result with no error.
- Expose the public API: `build_coverage(path, stories_dir, tests_dir, *, strict) -> CoverageResult`
  and `build_coverage_directory(directory, stories_dir, tests_dir, *, strict) -> list[CoverageResult]`.
</requirements>

<contract_rules>
R1 - Legacy-safe prompts
When a prompt has no <contract_rules> section,
the module MUST return a CoverageResult with has_contract_rules=False and empty rules and MUST NOT raise an exception.

R2 - Story linking
When a story__*.md file lacks a <!-- pdd-story-prompts: --> metadata comment,
the module MUST NOT count that story as evidence for any prompt.

R3 - Story cover extraction
When a linked story has a ## Covers section containing a rule reference such as R1 or prompt.prompt#R1,
the module MUST add that story filename to the evidence for the referenced rule.

R4 - Test evidence heuristic
When a test function name matches `test_R<N>_*` (case-insensitive), or a comment `# R<N>:` or `# covers R<N>` appears within 2 lines of a test function, or the docstring first line references R<N>,
the module MUST add that test function name to the evidence for R<N>.

R5 - Waiver precedence
When a rule has an active waiver from the prompt's <waivers> block or an explicit WAIVED W<N> entry in <coverage>,
the module MUST classify that rule as `waived` regardless of story or test evidence.

R6 - Failed evidence
When a linked story or test file has a validation failure (e.g. missing ## Acceptance Criteria, or a syntax error in a test that references the rule),
the module MUST classify that rule as `failed` and include the failure description.

R7 - Classification priority
When classifying a rule, the module MUST apply: waived > failed > checked > story-only > test-only > formal-only > unchecked.

R8 - Checked status
When a rule has at least one linked story and at least one test reference,
the module MUST classify it as `checked`.

R9 - Strict mode
When strict=True and a MUST or MUST NOT rule is unchecked or story-only,
`build_coverage` MUST set result.error to indicate the coverage gap.

R10 - Directory scan
When a directory is scanned, the module MUST return one CoverageResult per *.prompt file
and MUST skip *_LLM.prompt files.

R11 - Formal evidence
When a prompt's <formalization> block targets a rule (e.g. `rule_id: R1`),
the module MUST include that as formal evidence and classify the rule as `formal-only`
if no story or test evidence is present.
</contract_rules>

<vocabulary>
- coverage matrix: a per-prompt report mapping each contract rule to the evidence (stories, tests, formal) that covers it
- checked: a rule covered by both at least one user story and at least one executable test
- story-only: a rule covered by a linked story but no executable test
- test-only: a rule referenced by a test but not by any linked story
- unchecked: a rule with no story, test, or formal evidence
- waived: a rule explicitly waived in the prompt's <waivers> section; its coverage is approved by record
- failed: a rule whose coverage evidence is invalid (e.g. story missing Acceptance Criteria, test syntax error)
- formal-only: a rule with a <formalization> block but no story or test evidence
- pdd-story-prompts metadata: an HTML comment (`<!-- pdd-story-prompts: foo_python.prompt -->`) that links a story to one or more prompt files
- cross-module rule reference: a rule reference in the form `other_prompt.prompt#R3`, scoping the rule to a different prompt file
- strict mode: treats unchecked MUST/MUST NOT rules as errors rather than warnings
</vocabulary>

<acceptance_tests>
- `pytest tests/test_coverage_contracts.py tests/commands/test_coverage.py -q` MUST pass.
- `pdd coverage --contracts prompts/foo_python.prompt` MUST return a coverage table with one row per rule.
- A prompt with no <contract_rules> MUST return has_contract_rules=False with no error.
- A story with no <!-- pdd-story-prompts --> comment MUST NOT contribute evidence to any rule.
- A story linking to the target prompt with `## Covers` containing `R1` MUST add story evidence for R1.
- A test function named `test_R2_happy_path` MUST add test evidence for R2.
- A rule with WAIVED W1 in the <coverage> section MUST be classified as `waived` regardless of story/test evidence.
- A rule with both story and test evidence MUST be classified as `checked`.
- A rule with only story evidence MUST be classified as `story-only`.
- A rule with only test evidence MUST be classified as `test-only`.
- A rule with neither story, test, nor formal evidence MUST be classified as `unchecked`.
- In strict mode, an unchecked MUST rule MUST cause result.error to be set.
- `pdd coverage --contracts --json prompts/` MUST emit a JSON array of CoverageResult dicts.
- A directory scan MUST skip files named *_LLM.prompt.
</acceptance_tests>
